I was attending a course focused about biochemistry. Biochemistry is the science [slajd]. It brings together biology and chemistry as we can see by the name. The science focuses on processes that occur at a molecular level.
   I've learnt a lot of things about metabolism and synthetic biology. First I will present some basic topics of metabolism.
Enzymes are proteins that make the reaction occur faster. They are necessary for almost every reaction occuring in living organisms. They decrease activation energy which is the energy needed for reaction to occur.
   One of the most important metabolic pathway in our bodies is respiration.
It's a transformation of glucose (which we can get from food) into energy we are using to stay alive. The energy produced in respiration is stored in ATP which is adenoblabla [slajd].
Respiration can be aerobic (which means that oxygen is necessary for this proces) or anaerobic (without oxygen). Using oxygen we produce carbon dioxide and steam but in anaerobic respiration lactic acid or ethanol and carbon dioxide is produced.
Now let's think about why do we respire using oxygen. As we can see on the picture 2 particles of ATP are produced in anaerobic respiration. But in aerobic respiration we produce 30 particles of ATP. It means that aerobic respiration brings us much more energy.
   Now let's focus on synthetic biology.
It's the science that brings together molecular biology and engineering. It allows us to redesigning organisms for useful purposes. Very popular method used in synthetic biology is CRISPR-Cas. It's something like copy paste for DNA. It can be used to eliminate genetic diseases in humans. For example it's already used to insert malaria-blocking genes into mosquitoes or to introduce genes for disease resistance into wheat.
  Altough synthetic biology has a lot of potencial, it brings some ethical issues.
Genetic modification's opponents says that it is against nature to mess with DNA. And also this is new, not well-known technology, so it's risky. But on the other hand it gives us a lot of possibilities in medicine or agriculture. Also, we can develop our knowledge about molecular life.
   Biochemistry can be used to fight with global issues as a part of everyday life.
For example we can make our food become helthier. Scientists invented purple tomatoes. They contain antioxidant and anthcoÅtam [slajd] genes extracted from berries.
Seaweed contains alginate which helps to stop the body from digesting fat. We can extract alginate and incorprate it into other foods. That can help society fight with obesity. Also it has no side effects, it's natural and has no taste.

Everyone has some place which brings positive memories from childhood. It can be your grandma's home or playground that was near to your house or even a village where you used to travel on holidays.
For me, it is park in my neighborhood. There is a hill with ski slope on one side. From the top of the hill there is a magnificent view on Palace of Culture and Science and the whole city center. In the park there are a lot of green areas where you can relax or have a picnic. Also, there is a picturesque lake, but it is dangerous and forbidden to swim there. This is a perfect place for families with children because there are a few playgrounds.
When I think of this place, I remember a lof of things happening here in my life. When I was little, I used to ride a bike with my dad around the whole park. In winter I used to slide on sledge from the hill. When I was a little older, I used to go there after school with my two best friends. We used to climb on the tree and sit there for hours.
I think my childhood was amazing. I am really thankful for living near to such a great park.
